## Building an Animated Progress Bar in Vue 3

**Mental Model:** The core idea is to use a reactive `width` style property for the progress bar's inner element. When the `targetPercentage` changes, we'll update this `width` over time using a `watch` effect and `requestAnimationFrame` for smooth animation, rather than directly setting it, creating a visual transition.

### Step 1 — Create the `ProgressBar` component structure
Start by defining the basic HTML structure for your progress bar. You'll need an outer container and an inner element that represents the filled portion of the bar.

```vue
<template>
  <div class="progress-bar-container">
    <div class="progress-bar-fill" :style="fillStyle"></div>
  </div>
</template>

<script setup>
import { ref, computed } from 'vue';

const props = defineProps({
  targetPercentage: { type: Number, default: 0, validator: (val) => val >= 0 && val <= 100 }
});

const currentPercentage = ref(0);
const fillStyle = computed(() => ({
  width: `${currentPercentage.value}%`
}));
</script>

<style scoped>
.progress-bar-container {
  width: 100%;
  height: 20px;
  background-color: #e0e0e0;
  border-radius: 10px;
  overflow: hidden;
}

.progress-bar-fill {
  height: 100%;
  background-color: #4caf50;
  border-radius: 10px;
  transition: width 0.3s ease-out; /* Fallback transition */
}
</style>
```

### Step 2 — Implement the animation logic with `watch` and `requestAnimationFrame`
Use a `watch` effect on `targetPercentage` to trigger the animation. `requestAnimationFrame` will ensure smooth updates by synchronizing with the browser's rendering cycle, gradually incrementing or decrementing `currentPercentage` until it reaches the target.

```vue
<script setup>
import { ref, computed, watch, onUnmounted } from 'vue';

const props = defineProps({
  targetPercentage: { type: Number, default: 0, validator: (val) => val >= 0 && val <= 100 }
});

const currentPercentage = ref(0);
const animationFrameId = ref(null);

const animateProgress = () => {
  if (animationFrameId.value) {
    cancelAnimationFrame(animationFrameId.value);
  }

  const start = currentPercentage.value;
  const end = props.targetPercentage;
  const duration = 500; // ms
  let startTime = null;

  const step = (timestamp) => {
    if (!startTime) startTime = timestamp;
    const progress = (timestamp - startTime) / duration;

    if (progress < 1) {
      currentPercentage.value = start + (end - start) * progress;
      animationFrameId.value = requestAnimationFrame(step);
    } else {
      currentPercentage.value = end;
      animationFrameId.value = null;
    }
  };
  animationFrameId.value = requestAnimationFrame(step);
};

watch(() => props.targetPercentage, animateProgress, { immediate: true });

onUnmounted(() => {
  if (animationFrameId.value) {
    cancelAnimationFrame(animationFrameId.value);
  }
});

const fillStyle = computed(() => ({
  width: `${currentPercentage.value}%`,
  transition: 'none' // Disable CSS transition when JS animation is active
}));
</script>
```

### Step 3 — Add a demo in `App.vue`
Create a simple `App.vue` to demonstrate your `ProgressBar` component. Include buttons or sliders to easily change the `targetPercentage` prop and observe the animation.

```vue
<template>
  <div id="app">
    <h1>Animated Progress Bar Demo</h1>
    <ProgressBar :targetPercentage="progress" />
    <div class="controls">
      <button @click="setProgress(0)">0%</button>
      <button @click="setProgress(25)">25%</button>
      <button @click="setProgress(50)">50%</button>
      <button @click="setProgress(75)">75%</button>
      <button @click="setProgress(100)">100%</button>
      <input type="range" min="0" max="100" v-model.number="progress" />
      <span>{{ progress }}%</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</template>

<script setup>
import { ref } from 'vue';
import ProgressBar from './components/ProgressBar.vue';

const progress = ref(0);

const setProgress = (value) => {
  progress.value = value;
};
</script>

<style>
#app {
  font-family: Avenir, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;
  -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;
  -moz-osx-font-smoothing: grayscale;
  text-align: center;
  color: #2c3e50;
  margin-top: 60px;
  max-width: 600px;
  margin-left: auto;
  margin-right: auto;
}

.controls {
  margin-top: 20px;
  display: flex;
  gap: 10px;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: center;
}

.controls button {
  padding: 8px 15px;
  font-size: 16px;
  cursor: pointer;
}

.controls input[type="range"] {
  width: 150px;
}
</style>
```

**Edge Cases & Considerations:**

| Case                 | Handling                                                                                                                              |
| :------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| **Rapid updates**    | `cancelAnimationFrame` ensures only one animation is active, preventing visual glitches from quickly changing `targetPercentage`. |
| **Unmounting**       | `onUnmounted` hook cleans up any pending `requestAnimationFrame` calls to prevent memory leaks.                                 |
| **Invalid props**    | `validator` in `defineProps` ensures `targetPercentage` stays within [0, 100].                                                |
| **Initial render**   | `immediate: true` on the `watch` ensures the animation runs for the initial `targetPercentage` value.                           |

**Interview tip:** Discussing the choice between CSS transitions and `requestAnimationFrame` is a great point. While CSS transitions are simpler for basic effects, `requestAnimationFrame` offers more control, especially for complex, chained, or physics-based animations, and ensures better performance by syncing with the browser's refresh rate.

