## Build a Progress Bar in Angular

**Mental Model:** We'll create a simple Angular component that takes a `targetPercentage` input. Inside, we'll use CSS transitions to animate the width of an inner `div` to visually represent the progress. A button will trigger the update.

### Step 1 — Define the Component Structure
First, we'll set up our `AppComponent` with an inline template. The template will contain a container for the progress bar, an inner div whose width will change, and a button to trigger the animation.

```typescript
import { Component } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  template: `
    <div style="padding: 20px;">
      <h1>Progress Bar Demo</h1>
      <div style="width: 300px; height: 20px; background-color: #e0e0e0; border-radius: 10px; overflow: hidden;">
        <div
          [style.width]="currentWidth + '%'"
          style="height: 100%; background-color: #4CAF50; transition: width 0.5s ease-in-out;"
        ></div>
      </div>
      <button (click)="updateProgress()" style="margin-top: 15px; padding: 10px 20px; background-color: #007bff; color: white; border: none; border-radius: 5px; cursor: pointer;">
        Set Random Progress
      </button>
      <p style="margin-top: 10px;">Current Progress: {{ currentWidth | number:'1.0-0' }}%</p>
    </div>
  `,
  styles: []
})
export class AppComponent {
  currentWidth: number = 0;

  updateProgress(): void {
    // Implementation will go here
  }
}
```

### Step 2 — Implement the Progress Logic
We'll add a method `updateProgress` that generates a random target percentage and assigns it to `currentWidth`. Angular's change detection will then update the `[style.width]` binding, triggering the CSS transition.

```typescript
import { Component } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  template: `
    <div style="padding: 20px;">
      <h1>Progress Bar Demo</h1>
      <div style="width: 300px; height: 20px; background-color: #e0e0e0; border-radius: 10px; overflow: hidden;">
        <div
          [style.width]="currentWidth + '%'"
          style="height: 100%; background-color: #4CAF50; transition: width 0.5s ease-in-out;"
        ></div>
      </div>
      <button (click)="updateProgress()" style="margin-top: 15px; padding: 10px 20px; background-color: #007bff; color: white; border: none; border-radius: 5px; cursor: pointer;">
        Set Random Progress
      </button>
      <p style="margin-top: 10px;">Current Progress: {{ currentWidth | number:'1.0-0' }}%</p>
    </div>
  `,
  styles: []
})
export class AppComponent {
  currentWidth: number = 0;

  updateProgress(): void {
    const newProgress = Math.floor(Math.random() * 101); // Random number between 0 and 100
    this.currentWidth = newProgress;
  }
}
```

### Step 3 — Add Input for Controlled Progress (Optional but good for reusability)
To make the progress bar reusable, we can introduce an `@Input()` property for the target percentage. For this demo, we'll simulate it by having a fixed initial value and then updating it via the button.

```typescript
import { Component, OnInit } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  template: `
    <div style="padding: 20px;">
      <h1>Progress Bar Demo</h1>
      <div style="width: 300px; height: 20px; background-color: #e0e0e0; border-radius: 10px; overflow: hidden;">
        <div
          [style.width]="currentWidth + '%'"
          style="height: 100%; background-color: #4CAF50; transition: width 0.5s ease-in-out;"
        ></div>
      </div>
      <button (click)="updateProgress()" style="margin-top: 15px; padding: 10px 20px; background-color: #007bff; color: white; border: none; border-radius: 5px; cursor: pointer;">
        Set Random Progress
      </button>
      <p style="margin-top: 10px;">Current Progress: {{ currentWidth | number:'1.0-0' }}%</p>
    </div>
  `,
  styles: []
})
export class AppComponent implements OnInit {
  currentWidth: number = 0;

  ngOnInit(): void {
    this.currentWidth = 25; // Initial progress
  }

  updateProgress(): void {
    const newProgress = Math.floor(Math.random() * 101); // Random number between 0 and 100
    this.currentWidth = newProgress;
  }
}
```

**Edge Cases:**

*   **Invalid Percentage Input:** Ensure the `currentWidth` is always clamped between 0 and 100. Values outside this range might cause visual glitches or unexpected behavior.
*   **Performance on frequent updates:** For very rapid updates, consider debouncing or throttling the input to avoid excessive DOM manipulation, though CSS transitions are generally efficient.

**Interview tip:** Explain how Angular's change detection combined with CSS transitions makes this animation straightforward. Mention the benefits of using `[style.width]` for dynamic styling and the `transition` CSS property for smooth animations.

